{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:25:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:25:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18471"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.49,0.28,0.02,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6647"},{"type":"tags","id":"6649"},{"type":"tags","id":"6650"},{"type":"tags","id":"9842"},{"type":"tags","id":"9843"},{"type":"tags","id":"9844"},{"type":"tags","id":"9872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood flow through the systemic circulation involves complex changes in pressure, velocity, and vessel characteristics as blood moves from the aorta to the capillaries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes blood flow in systemic arteries?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood velocity remains constant from aorta to arterioles","Blood pressure and velocity progressively decrease from aorta to arterioles","Blood pressure increases in smaller arteries","Blood velocity increases in arterioles","Blood pressure remains constant throughout the arterial system"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood pressure and velocity progressively decrease from aorta to arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E due to increasing vascular resistance and total cross-sectional area as vessels branch into smaller segments. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood velocity remains constant from aorta to arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as velocity decreases due to the increased total cross-sectional area with vessel branching. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlood pressure increases in smaller arteries\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as blood pressure actually decreases as blood moves further from the heart due to friction and resistance. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlood velocity increases in arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as blood velocity decreases in smaller vessels due to increased total cross-sectional area. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlood pressure remains constant throughout the arterial system\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as pressure gradually decreases due to resistance from vessel walls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe greatest drop in pressure occurs across the arterioles, which are the primary resistance vessels in the systemic circulation. The decrease in velocity is due to the principle of continuity, where flow velocity must decrease as total cross-sectional area increases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood pressure is highest in the aorta and gradually decreases as blood flows through progressively smaller arteries and arterioles.","Arterioles are the primary site of vascular resistance in the systemic circulation.","The total cross-sectional area of blood vessels increases as they branch, causing blood flow velocity to decrease from aorta to capillaries."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 14; pg. 172","Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:28:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:28:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11200"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"desc